<|channel|>analysis<|message|>We need to produce reasoning steps.<|end|><|start|>assistant<|channel|>final<|message|>The ionization energy of an excited He atom equals the ground‑state ionization potential minus the energy needed to reach the excited level.

1. Convert the wavelength of the transition (58.44 nm) to photon energy.
   \[
   E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
   \]
   Use \(h=6.626\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s}\), \(c=2.998\times10^{8}\,\text{m s}^{-1}\),
   and \(\lambda =58.44\times10^{-9}\,\text{m}\).

2. Compute the energy in joules:
   \[
   E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{6.626\times10^{-34}\times 2.998\times10^{8}}
                         {58.44\times10^{-9}}
                     =3.39\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}
   \]

3. Convert joules to electron‑volts using \(1\,\text{eV}=1.602\times10^{-19}\,\text{J}\):
   \[
   E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{3.39\times10^{-18}\,\text{J}}
                           {1.602\times10^{-19}\,\text{J/eV}}
                     =21.2\,\text{eV}
   \]

4. The excited state lies 21.2 eV above the ground state, so the energy required to remove an electron from this excited configuration is reduced by that amount:
   \[
   I_{\text{excited}}=I_{\text{ground}}-E_{\text{photon}}
                     =24.6\,\text{eV}-21.2\,\text{eV}
                     =3.4\,\text{eV}
   \]

Solution:
The photon energy is
E = hc/λ = 6.626x10^-34 J s x 2.998x10^8 m s^-1 / 58.44x10^-9 m x 1J / 1.602x10^-19 J = 21.2eV
Therefore, the ionization energy of the He atom in this state is 24.6eV - 21.2eV = 3.4eV.

